===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|husbonde|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|husbonda|hūsbonda|lang=ang}}, {{term|husbunda|hūsbunda|male head of a household, householder, master of a house|lang=ang}}, probably from {{etyl|non}} {{term|húsbóndi||lang=non|master of house}}, from {{term|hús||house|lang=non}} + {{term|bóndi||dweller, householder|lang=non}}, equivalent to {{compound|house|bond|t2=serf, slave|lang=en}}. Cognate with Icelandic {{term|húsbóndi||head of household|lang=is}}, Faroese {{term|húsbóndi||husband|lang=fo}}, Norwegian {{term|husbond||head of household, husband|lang=no}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|husbonde||master|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|husbonde||husband|lang=da}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{obsolete}} The [[master]] of a [[house]]; the [[head]] of a [[family]]; a [[householder]].
# {{obsolete}} A [[tiller]] of the [[ground]]; a [[husbandman]].
# {{archaic}} A [[prudent]] or [[frugal]] [[manager]].
# A [[man]] in a marriage or marital relationship, especially in relation to his spouse.
# {{context|UK}} A [[manager]] of [[property]]; one who has the care of another's belongings, [[owndom]], or [[interests]]; a [[steward]]; an [[economist]].
# Large [[cushion]] with arms meant to support a person in the sitting position.
#: ''While reading her book, Sally leaned back against her '''husband''', wishing it were the human kind.''
# {{context|UK|_|dialectal}} A [[poll]]ed [[tree]]; a [[pollard]].

